Experiment performed at the 4MV KN
accelerator at the University of Notre Dame Nuclear
Science Laboratory
Targets were prepared by
anodization of 0.3 mm thick tantalum backings using
H2O enriched to 97.2% in 18-O. This process is known
to produce homogeneous films of (Ta)2(O)5. The target
thickness was chosen to be about 9 keV of energy loss
for an alpha beam of 1000 keV and a target
orientation of 90deg. with respect to the beam
direction.
The high energy data (E(alpha) > 1530 keV) were
taken with an unshielded 20% efficiency Ge detector
setup. Due to the decrease in yield at lower energies
and the natural 214Pb background line at E(gamma) =
351.9 keV a Ge detector with higher efficiency (55%)
shielded with lead against room background was used
to measure the reaction yield down to the n1
threshold at E(alpha) = 1280 keV. In both cases the
target was mounted at an angle of 45deg with respect
to the beam direction.
Yield was determined from the intensity of the gamma
ray deexciting first excited state at 350.7 keV
